{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:29:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:29:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18178"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18178"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10892"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64578"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe obliquus capitis inferior is one of the muscles located in the suboccipital region of the neck. It is part of the group of muscles that contribute to movements of the head and neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of this muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevation of the scapula","Extension of the head","Flexion of the head","Lateral flexion of the head","Rotation of the atlas on the axis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the obliquus capitis inferior is the \u003Cstrong\u003Erotation of the atlas on the axis\u003C/strong\u003E. This muscle originates from the spinous process of the axis (C2) and inserts on the transverse process of the atlas (C1), allowing it to facilitate rotational movement at the atlantoaxial joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexion of the head\u003C/strong\u003E - This action is primarily performed by anterior neck muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtension of the head\u003C/strong\u003E - This action is performed by other suboccipital muscles, but not the obliquus capitis inferior \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral flexion of the head\u003C/strong\u003E - This action involves other muscles such as the sternocleidomastoid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevation of the scapula\u003C/strong\u003E - This action is performed by muscles like the trapezius and levator scapulae\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe obliquus capitis inferior is unique among the suboccipital muscles as it does not attach to the skull, focusing instead on the rotation of the first cervical vertebra on the second.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The obliquus capitis inferior muscle is responsible for rotation of the atlas on the axis.","The obliquus capitis inferior is the only suboccipital muscle that does not attach to the skull.","The obliquus capitis inferior plays a role in stabilising the atlantoaxial joint."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18178"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T20:47:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T20:48:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10892"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79236"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name"